Wantful had a number of other high-profile investors, including Polaris Venture

When the company launched ahead of the holiday shopping season in 2011, it
began by offering personalized product recommendations for those you were
buying gifts for, after you first provided the site with information about your
friend’s gender, tastes and preferences. Around a year later, the company
introduced what it called “phase two” of its vision, introducing both an iPad
application and print magazine to the lineup.
At this time, Wantful began moving away from gift-giving and toward more
personalized e-commerce. That is, instead of just finding gifts for friends and
family, users could find items for themselves as well. But this move also put the
startup up against a host of competitors, including other e-commerce services
and aggregators like Wanelo, Wish, Fancy, Want, Svpply’s Want, Polyvore, and
In addition to the iPad app which blended both content and commerce, Wantful
also tried a different approach by sending its most active customers their own
personalized, print magazine featuring stories about retailers and products.
Today, the Wantful website informs visitors that the company has suspended
operations, but customers can reach out via email for support. (Clicking the “OK”
button to close the message just feels wrong, though, you know?) Wantful had a
number of happy customers, and the service will be missed.
Still, it seems inevitable there will be some consolidation in the personalized
e-commerce space in the months ahead, so stay tuned.
